\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Demand studies in the developing world often work with data that is much
 sparser and has overall less details on the individual households.
 Current surveys mitigate many such issues - but the problems that arise
 out of non-uniform institutions themselves make the standardisation of
 data across the developing countries rather challenging.
 Studies of consumption of quality in the developing countries have therefore
 often limited themselves to food where the measurement of quality is independen
t of consumed brand or type - details that are often not recorded in a typical
 consumer survey.
 Since a significant chunk of income is spent on food for most of the population
 in the developing countries, the variation in quality in food gives us
 a good picture of quality substitution.
 Still, problems like segmentation of price - due lack of a cheap transport
 infrastructure and sufficiently large firm sizes - makes the analysis of
 quality particularly prone to error.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the current study, we attempt to quantify the choice of quality in the
 developing world.
 Instead of focusing on food quality alone, we also observe the effect of
 vast differences in life-style that living in urban vs rural areas would
 bring to the consumer in a developing country.
 The sheer lack of availability of certain goods in the rural areas - we
 believe - should also be noted in the consumption of quality.
 We comment on how overall quality may vary with economic inequalities across
 multiple economies as the consumer spreads the expenditure on quality across
 the commodity groups (food, energy etc.).
 This may provide us a better understanding of how quality of consumption
 changes in response to vast economic changes such as urban developments
 or market centralisation.
 This could be of interest both from a general demand analysis perspective
 and from a more specific conspicuous consumption perspective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To observe quality of consumption with respect to income inequalities across
 the developing countries, we motivate a model for substitution between
 a consumer's long-term needs that are fulfilled with ownership of assets
 or improvement of the socio-economic standing and the consumer's short-term
 needs that are fulfilled with an improved quality of consumption.
 The socio-economic standing of the consumer is determined by an order of
 what we identify as the parameters for status (income, education, occupation)
 as well as a history of quality of consumption.
 Needless to say, these parameters do not all have the same effect on the
 long-term socio-economic standing of the consumer.
 The improvement in quality of expenditure is measured with the expensive
 non-durable consumption (ENDC).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The aim of assessing this substitution is to understand how the distribution
 of quality across the consumption groups (food, energy, housing etc.) should
 be affected by the long-term needs of (accumulation of durable goods, education
al needs etc.) which don't necessarily fall in the same separable commodity
 groups that we record in a typical consumer survey.
 It is also worth emphasising that we differentiate between quality consumption
 and conspicuous consumption.
 At least semantically speaking, the term conspicuous consumption encompasses
 only the exclusive consumption by the rich.
 Even though there are similarities between the current developments in
 Africa and the the rapid economic developments took place in the United
 States in the late 19th century as the latter's economy transitioned from
 a vastly agrarian society to an industrialised one, there are issue with
 extending the concepts identified by Veblen into modern economic theory.
 In the environment of the nascent economic transition in sub-Saharan Africa
 where severe economic inequalities are still observed, the options for
 conspicuous consumption as such are limited to a very small part of the
 population.
 The quality consumption and possession of long-term assets - on the other
 hand - are concerns for a larger section of the population that contribute
 to a consumer's long-term utility.
 Status - which can be seen as part of the long-term utility of the consumer
 - a rather complex social psychological phenomenon.
 One cannot thus make judgments on whether an items is a status good or
 not by observing consumer data alone.
 For example, if one were to rely only on whether an item can be afforded
 by the rich - then electricity, being used by a small and rich part of
 the population in a sub-Saharan African country like Tanzania, may appear
 to be a status good - at par with weddings which are a clear way of indicating
 status.
 Whether the same amount of money spent on weddings enhances status more
 than when it's spent on electricity is still a difficult question to answer
 - as it is a complex interaction of supply, wealth, assets and social identity
 that determine status in a society.
 As soon as one attempts to understand the underlying factors that contribute
 to status in the developing world, one cannot rely on the static assumption
 of a set of items being 
\shape italic
conspicuous
\shape default
.
 In Tanzania again, one may be tempted to argue - based on the literature
 on conspicuous consumption - that buying clothes indicates higher status.
 But without observing the effect that getting electricity in the house
 or moving to a bigger house may have on a consumer's long-term utility,
 we cannot accurately explain the household consumption on status - since
 the possibility that those spending on electricity or housing may actually
 be cutting down on clothing expenditure while deriving status from electricity
 or house ownership cannot be ruled out.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The literature on conspicuous consumption seems more impassioned and a little
 too wide-ranging in its conclusions from a the discussion on elasticities
 of a typical demand survey.
 In an attempt to limit our discussion to measurable criteria, we identify
 methods for identification of short-term and long-term needs.
 The typical standard diary and recall methods in a survey measure neither
 the quality of consumption nor the socio-economic standing of the consumer
 - which we wish to embark upon in the study.
 As it turns out, the measurement of quality is relatively easy - if we
 rely on the availability of price information to classify high-quality
 (expensive) items apart from their cheaper substitutes.
 In the Tanzanian LSMS data therefore, eggs and milk are deemed of lower
 quality than goat and beef for proteins.
 Similarly for transport, bicycle is deemed of lower quality than car and
 so on.
 Except for some items that would be missing in the developing country when
 comparing the consumption between two countries, this is a relatively easy
 task.
 For the more difficult task of measuring the socio-economic standing of
 a consumer
