\end_inset

, we rely on the measure of socio-economic-status (SES) - which is a standard
 measure of the socio-economic status often used in the sociological and
 health studies.
 The long-term utility of the consumer in the model thus consists of a vector
 of income, education and region/locality/neighborhood.
 In addition, we also include the ownership of durable goods (defined as
 items to be purchased with an intent of long-term ownership) and a history
 of expensive non-durable consumption (hereon abbreviated as ENDC) in the
 measures for status.
 This is of key importance since income, education, occupation or residence
 are usually fixed in the short-run.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our goal in the current chapter is to not explore status consumption per
 se - but rather outline how status-related consumption could be viewed
 in a conventional model for consumer demand.
 To comment on status consumption, we base ourselves on the assertion that
 if consumption for status does exist, it must appear in the long-term utility
 for the rational consumer in a model.
 In other words, for a rational consumer to spend on status consumption,
 she must see some status utility from consumption in the long-term or the
 short-term.
 We don't attempt to explain whether status is a long-term concern or a
 short-term concern for the consumer - as it is a matter of social observation.
 Similarly, it is an issue of social psychological judgment - if not ideology
 - to conclude that individuals buying durable goods as their income increases
 is a matter of status consumption (and thus a waste) and not simply social
 mobility.
 Regardless of what one views as status consumption, we can test from the
 data whether expensive nondurable consumption increases with changes towards
 industrialisation (as seems to be the case when reading Veblen) or that
 expensive nondurable consumption is always used to compensate for not having
 as much as status and durable goods as others.
 If non-durable consumption is indeed correlated with social mobility (i.e.
 purchase of assets or an upward movement in education and occupation for
 a member of the household) or if those who don't see any changes in long-term
 possession of assets or changes in occupation-rank or education levels,
 continue to maintain high non-durable consumption in face of price changes,
 then we may have something to say about how non-durable consumption matters
 to the household.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our basic framework can be used to compare the developing and the developed
 economies as well.
 Since the durable goods have a higher upfront cost compared to the quality
 consumption, the accumulation of durable goods is a clear indicator tifhe
 consumer's high expectation of the stability of her income if not a real
 stability of high income.
 We thus compare the accumulation of long-term durable goods (LTDG) in a
 developed economy with that of in developing economy by ordering the LTDG
 in the markets based on their cost of acquisition.
 The differences in the costs of the two successive LTDG in this 
