\begin_layout Section
Literature Review
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the study of consumer preferences over time, the tendencies of habit
 formation have been noted by both the behavioural and classical approaches.
 The measurement of the effect of change in habits and quality on the consumer
 price has in fact had a long tradition (see Fisher-Shell
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FisherShell1968"

\end_inset

 for a classical treatment).
 In the demand analysis literature, Muellbauer
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "MuellbauerRationalityMyopia1988."

\end_inset

 points out that a model for myopia amongst consumers could explain their
 preferences better.
 In later works where a general setting of the intertemporal substitution
 problem in a life-cycle context is used, a rational utility-optimising
 consumer can balance between the non-durable and durable consumption based
 on her planned and actual savings over her life-time.
 This is the setting explored by a few recent behavioural approaches (see
 Shefrin-Thaler 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ShefrinThaler1988"

\end_inset

) that have attempted to model the rules of mental accounting that could
 be used by the consumers.
 Such models can explain consumers' inertia of choices and allow the representat
ive consumer to be influenced by behavioural factors such as willpower rather
 than be subservient to an optimised plan for life-time savings and consumption.
 In an attempt to model real-life consumption patterns, the representative
 consumer in such a model is subject to accumulating items that she doesn't
 need or acquiring habits of consumption she could barely afford in the
 long-term.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is possible to view the role of social identities in relation to how
 assets are accumulated over generations and passed on as endowments as
 well.
 Empirical studies in both the developed world and the developing countries
 have found social group identities relevant to consumption (see Chao et
 al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chao1998"

\end_inset

, Charles et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "CharlesHurstRace"

\end_inset

, Omori et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "OmoriSmithVisRace"

\end_inset

 and Khamis et al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ZahraIndia"

\end_inset

).
 A behavioural model can explain such behaviour with the introduction of
 reference points in the utility function (see Markowitz Utility).
 The relevance of reference points isn't limited to laboratory experiment
 contexts.
 For example, Robert Frank
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FrankPond"

\end_inset

 finds that signaling needs become more important amongst the lower economic
 strata when they are huddled in the overpopulated suburban areas of big
 cities in the US.
 A more general approach to social order is proposed by Corneo et al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "corneo_snobbism"

\end_inset

 and Coleman
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ColemanSocialTheory1990"

\end_inset

 who motivate the case for a ranking order of status while attempting to
 measure the tendency of the consumer to move herself up in the ranking
 order.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the developing countries, urban industrialisation and overpopulation
 in the is likely to create vast difference in the life-styles between urban
 and rural areas.
 Although a detailed time-series of consumption microdata matching the respectiv
e quality in the developed world is hardly available in the developing countries
, the framework for risk preferences has often been used by microeconomists
 to understand the consumer demand.
 An important economic model for urban and rural interactions is the Lewis
 model 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GollinLRF"

\end_inset

 - which views urban migration as a necessary phase of development - leading
 to a competition between industrial and agricultural sectors for labour
 and food (it predicts the prices of food to rise as labour moves from agricultu
re to industry).
 The worker/farmer is meant to maximise her income and reduce the risk associate
d with it as she is faced with the choice of migration to the urban areas.
 We note that a flight to urban areas is often not only an escape from desponden
t circumstances but also an access to expanded consumption basket and a
 chance for improbable social mobilities.
 A model that accounts for the competition amongst the individuals for status
 or a place in a perceived social order - therefore - could refine such
 a model by adding more incentives to migration.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The literature has associated the finer trends in consumption with the interacti
on between the introduction of industrial goods and the status needs of
 the consumers.
 Deaton and Dreze
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeatonDrezeIndiaFood"

\end_inset

 explain a relevant problem in rapidly industrialising countries by exploring
 the squeeze in food budget in India.
 Sen
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Sen2005Calories"

\end_inset

 has attributed this squeeze to the rise in the poverty-level for consumption
 of non-food items.
 From a behavioural perspective, this would amount to the change in the
 reference points for non-food consumption.
 An issue with the use of reference points, however, is its measurement
 in the large-scale microdata.
 Unlike in the controlled settings of an experiment, where the reference
 points can be specified more clearly, they are more difficult to justify
 in the consumption microdata.
 But so long as a separation between the bare neessities and luxuries can
 be justified, a framework for measurement of consumption can be used to
 understand change in needs of a society.
 Studying the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

visible
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 consumption in the regions of erstwhile East and West Germany, for example,
 Friehe et al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FrieheGermany"

\end_inset

 attempt to answer whether prolonged measures of income equality (and therefore
 stagnant ownership of durable goods) can influence non-durable consumption
 asymmetrically when there is a sudden rise in incomes.
 If the macroeconomic factors and issues of supply (e.g.
 income inequalities, distribution of resources etc.) can be controlled for
 in the data, then a model for long-term (or more stable) needs against
 short-term (or more uncertain) needs can explain the demand pressures induced
 by the differences in the developed and developing states of economies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the current chapter we attempt to measure how consumers may balance their
 long-term and short-term needs as the market introduces new durable goods
 and the improved quality over time.
 The perceptions of consumers do not serve as an input to the current model
