\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From a behavioural economics perspective, it is possible to view the consumer's
 preference to long-term protection as a perception of risk.
 Thus one could model status in the long-term utility of the consumer as
 a probability of promotion to a state of higher income and assets (or any
 characteristic that is perceived to have a higher stability of incomes).
 The status-differences - viewed as a probability of social mobility - could
 therefore vary across countries and time - depending on how individuals
 place themselves in a perceived (risky) social order.
 Further, if severe social stratification doesn't exist in the societies,
 then it is fair to assume that through social interactions, those spending
 more on higher quality and acquiring long-term durable goods over time
 would increase their likelihood of being in a higher status category (for
 future generations if not for themselves).
 Thus status could be connected with the consumption in a model - letting
 us explain how the former could change over time as consumers act on the
 (subjective) probability of status promotion.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That the differences in purchasing power between the sections of a society
