 them in the social order).
 On the other hand, when a minimum degree of education isn't provided by
 the state (as is the case in the developing world), a consumer would associate
 higher risk with the expected growth in education.
 Thus indirectly, education is more likely to matter for expected status
 (or even income growth).
 In a model that can compare two economies with a different degree of state
 support, the strength of institutions determines the expectation of accumulatio
n of public goods (such as family education level) and how much education
 may matter for long-term status.
 The latter is however influenced by how markets evolve to provide expanded
 consumption choices to the consumer.
